ion of &quot;success?&quot;<br><br>Valquiss seems to be determining &quot;failure&quot; as &quot;not enough people will play there and continue to play there enough to sustain the cost of running the server.&quot;  I doubt that it will fail in this regard.  With over 350,000+ subscribers, many of them avid enough about the game to buy another PC, another copy of the game and expansions, and pay for a second account, I think it's clear that there are definitely going to be a lot of people who are willing to pay $40/month to play on a &quot;premium&quot; special services server, providing Verant even kind of lives up to their end of the bargain.  They're capping the server at 10,000 subscribers to begin with, so obviously in their accounting they've determined they can turn a profit with that many subscribers.  I think they will be able to get about that many, or nearly that many people interested without much trouble.<br><br>Sure, the majority of us AREN'T willing to pay that much, but if even 1 in 10, or 1 in 20 people are willing to pay that much, it will be a success for Verant.<br><br>Now, it's an entirely different question if you're asking PLAYERS to determine success.  For Verant, success is determined easily: if it makes money, it's a success, if it doesn't, it's a failure.<br><br>For players, whether or not the server is a success will be determined by whether or not they're satisified with the play on the server.  Some people are satisified with FV, and for them (for me) the server has been a huge success.  Some people have been dissatisfied with the way the server has turned out, and for them, it represents a failure.<br><br>I think that from a roleplaying point of view, the &quot;Legends&quot; server is going to be little better than a &quot;blue&quot; server for roleplaying, and in fact probably worse for roleplaying.  Roleplaying is done between <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  people</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Dynamic content only provides a backdrop.  A good backdrop is nice, but if the roleplayers aren't there, the roleplaying won't happen.<br><br>I think that the Legends server may very possibly succeed in satisfying very goal-oriented players (&quot;powergamers&quot;, &quot;achievers&quot;) because the dynamic content may very well mean a dynamic challenge, which should satisfy such players... as will the pride associated with being the first person to obtain &quot;Uber Item X&quot; and having it named after them.<br><br>For &quot;casual gamers&quot;... well, I think it might very well be an entertaining server for your average/casual EQ gamer, if the average/casual EQ gamer were willing to spend $30 extra a month on the game.<br><br>So, if it succeeds for you?  That's great.  If it doesn't?  Sorry.  If it is a failure for Verant, I can see Valquiss's point that this might be a good thing for the ~390,000 of us who aren't willing to pay $30/month for the extras, but would welcome some of the extra web based features that might trickle down to us for free, or at a discounted price.<br><br>Heck, for the web based features, I might be willing to spend $5-10 extra per month.  For more responsive tech support/customer service (if I could be assured of a response to my petition within 45 minutes, for example) I think I'd definitely be willing to spend $10 extra per month for the web based features and the better service, without the dynamic content, new server or any of the other jazz.<br><br>So if it succeeds?  It means nothing to us happy FVers, except that maybe we lose a few of our RPers and PGers to legends.<br><br>If it fails?  Well, if it fails, maybe we have some neat new features to look forward to. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>Player of Velsor Secarne (on Firiona Vie)<BR>Shadow Knight of Cazic-Thule<BR>Seeker of the Dark Truth<BR>Officer of the <A HREF="http://www.geocities.com/theindigovoid">Indigo Void</A><BR>Fluent in Human, Erudite, Teir'Dal,